WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
Thank you all for taking some time out of your day.

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:15.820
We're going to start by looking at an R Markdown document and how we can use R and Python together

00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:21.280
inside of that document with some special new magic that's available in the latest versions

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.280
of RStudio.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.959
We'll also talk about how once we've finished that document, it can be published and shared

00:00:27.959 --> 00:00:31.480
in a reproducible way so that others can view it.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:35.080
And perhaps you might introduce some lightweight automation.

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:39.200
We'll look briefly at how a similar outcome can be achieved with Jupyter notebooks using

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:41.459
shared infrastructure.

00:00:41.459 --> 00:00:47.360
And then we'll talk about how the model we're creating in this document can actually be

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:52.279
put into place so that decisions can be made based on that model.

00:00:52.279 --> 00:00:56.480
And we'll look at how you can maybe do that with an interactive app or through something

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:57.480
like a RESTful API.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:03.840
And then finally, we'll talk about how those APIs and applications can also be developed

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:08.320
using some of the new options inside of the RStudio tool set.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:11.620
So we'll go ahead and jump in.

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:17.599
And to set a little bit of context, I am using RStudio on a server.

00:01:17.599 --> 00:01:21.639
And so that means I'm going to access RStudio through a web browser.

00:01:21.639 --> 00:01:24.519
And there's a couple of really nice benefits to doing this.

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:30.800
The first is that I have more resources available to me than I would on my laptop.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:35.760
And specifically, if I go in to start a new session, you'll see we're taking advantage

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.680
of a tool called Kubernetes that allows me to kind of on-demand specify what resources

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:43.839
I want for this work.

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:49.599
Another benefit of using a server is that it means everyone on my team, Lou and myself,

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:52.199
are speaking from a common playbook.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:01:56.599
And in this case, we're explicitly defining our environment through a Docker image where

00:01:56.599 --> 00:01:57.959
our session is going to run.

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:03.120
But even if you're not using Kubernetes or Docker, by having your work on a server, everyone

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:07.199
has a common home, which helps make collaboration a lot easier.

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:11.639
And then finally, because we're on a server, we're a lot closer to our data, which means

00:02:11.639 --> 00:02:13.800
our work can scale in an easier fashion.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:17.000
Now, in a moment, I'll be jumping into the RStudio IDE.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.240
But while I'm here, I just want to point out that one of the things we've done in the last

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:27.399
year for multilingual teams is added the ability for other editing tools to be accessed

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:29.320
from this same interface.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.479
So it's almost like a workbench, where you can pick up the right tool from that workbench

00:02:33.479 --> 00:02:38.559
regardless of what language your current project demands.

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:43.000
And that means for multilingual data science teams, everyone has all those benefits I just

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.279
described of a common playbook, regardless of what editor they're using.

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:51.279
And for IT, it's really nice to have this common front door where these different environments

00:02:51.279 --> 00:02:53.919
are going to be accessed.

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:57.240
So we'll go ahead and jump into RStudio.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:00.559
And at this point, I want to point out that everything you're going to see inside of the

00:03:00.559 --> 00:03:08.000
RStudio IDE, even though I'm using RStudio Server, is going to be available in any flavor

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.720
of the RStudio IDE.

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:13.919
So whether you're using the open source desktop, or RStudio Server open source, or the professional

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:20.399
product like I am, you'll have access to the interoperability that we're about to go through.

00:03:20.399 --> 00:03:26.000
So to set the stage just a little bit more, I'm doing my work here inside of an R Markdown

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:27.000
document.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.679
If you haven't seen R Markdown before, it's basically a format where I can combine prose,

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:38.759
so what I'm thinking, along with my code, and then the output of my code.

00:03:38.759 --> 00:03:42.399
But what's new in the latest version of RStudio is something that we're calling the visual

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:43.399
editor.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:48.320
And what that means is that even though I'm editing in R Markdown document, on the fly,

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:51.839
I'm getting a live rendering of what this document looks like.

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:55.440
So that means I can do things a little bit easier than I used to.

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:00.720
So for example, if I needed to put in a table, I could insert a table really quickly.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:05.520
I can add Markdown to that table, and it will be rendered on demand.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.240
I can even do things like insert citations or emojis.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:16.799
And so I can use all these different tools inside of the visual editor, and whatever

00:04:16.799 --> 00:04:20.760
I'm doing is going to show up as kind of a real-time preview.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:25.679
And the reason why I think this is so important is that regardless of what language you're

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:31.279
working from, ultimately, a data scientist's key job is to communicate.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:35.600
And so being able to write effectively in a tool that supports really rich technical

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:40.279
communication is vital for any type of data scientist.

00:04:40.279 --> 00:04:44.239
And I've found that this visual editor makes things that used to be challenging for that

00:04:44.239 --> 00:04:47.679
type of technical communication really easy.

00:04:47.679 --> 00:04:51.799
One of my favorites is I can go in here and actually insert an image.

00:04:51.799 --> 00:04:56.000
I don't have to worry about figuring out where that image lives on disk, and I can even resize

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.200
it interactively.

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:03.079
So we hope that regardless of what language, this visual editor is going to give you a

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:08.239
head start as you're writing down what you're thinking and documenting your process.

00:05:08.239 --> 00:05:13.760
And it really combines kind of the best worlds of a Jupyter notebook and the RStudio IDE

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:14.760
and R Markdown.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:19.000
And if you haven't seen this before, inside the latest version of RStudio, all you need

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.359
to do is click this button in the upper right-hand corner.

00:05:22.359 --> 00:05:27.920
And what that button does is flip us back and forth between the plain text source code

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.720
that's still available here, perfect for version control, and that pre-rendered view of the

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:33.720
document.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:38.640
All right, so that's where we're doing our work, is inside of this visual editor.

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:39.640
What are we going to do?

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:43.440
Well, we have kind of a made-up data science exercise.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.799
And so like most data science exercises, we're going to start by pulling in some data.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:50.279
And this data is coming from a database.

00:05:50.279 --> 00:05:54.480
And again, something that we're excited about, regardless of what language you use, is the

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:59.760
ability within RStudio to seamlessly manage connections to databases.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.079
And so here I have a connection to a database called content.

00:06:02.079 --> 00:06:04.839
There's a number of different tables inside of it.

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:10.079
And without switching to a different SQL editor, I can really easily preview the schema of

00:06:10.079 --> 00:06:14.320
this database table and even preview some of the records if I want.

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:17.279
So I have this database.

00:06:17.279 --> 00:06:22.119
And I'm starting out by writing some R code that's going to operate within the database

00:06:22.119 --> 00:06:24.359
to do some basic transforms.

00:06:25.239 --> 00:06:30.200
And so if you haven't seen this before, using dplyr, you can write R code, then that R code

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:32.440
actually gets executed as SQL.

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.320
And so that's what's going on here.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:40.200
So we're creating some data that we're then going to do an analysis on.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:43.160
So let's take a quick look at that data.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.640
Essentially, we have spatial temporal data.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.519
And so we're looking at bike share data from the DC area.

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:54.160
So those bike shares, if you've ever been walking around the city and you want to rent

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:58.399
a bike, you can usually find a station with bikes lined up, and then you pay some money

00:06:58.399 --> 00:07:00.200
to be able to ride the bike around.

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:06.160
And so the data that we have is how many bikes were available at any given station at any

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:07.480
point in time.

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:11.559
So we have kind of this time series of bikes that are available.

00:07:11.559 --> 00:07:16.600
Then we also have kind of spatial component of where those bikes were located.

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:18.239
So it's a pretty cool data set.

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:23.519
And what we want to try to do is forecast into the future for a given station, how many

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:24.880
bikes might be available.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:31.359
Say I have to commute home at 5 p.m., is there going to be a bike there that I can take?

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:35.839
So we'll get started by doing that in R. And the first thing that we're going to do is

00:07:35.839 --> 00:07:38.640
create a test and training data set.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:42.720
And because we're working with time series data, it's really important that we don't

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.760
accidentally use the future to predict the past.

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:51.519
And so in R, we've created a test and training data set where the training data set sequentially

00:07:51.519 --> 00:07:55.160
occurs before the test data set.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:59.799
And now that we have these two things, we can go ahead and build our model.

00:07:59.799 --> 00:08:05.480
And I'm using a new R package or an ecosystem of R packages called tidy models.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:09.880
There's a lot of great resources online if you want to dive into modeling in R. But essentially

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:16.079
what this set of packages is allowing us to do is pre-process our data.

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:19.000
And so we have here kind of latitude and longitude.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:20.600
That's the spatial element.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.519
We have the date and time.

00:08:22.519 --> 00:08:24.480
That's the temporal element.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:29.440
But we've used some pre-processing tricks to create a factor for the day of week and

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:32.520
also add some information about whether a given day was a holiday.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:36.159
So you have a nice, rich data set to do modeling on.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:42.919
And then the first thing that we might do is create a model in R. And so to do that,

00:08:42.919 --> 00:08:48.039
again, within this tidy models ecosystem, I'm essentially creating a workflow that's

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:54.919
going to take our model pre-processing along with this gradient-boosted engine and fit

00:08:54.919 --> 00:08:57.559
a simple regression model.

00:08:57.559 --> 00:08:59.679
So we can go ahead and do that.

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:07.000
And if we look at the results here, we have a predicted number of bikes along with the

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.559
actual number of bikes, kind of what we'd expect.

00:09:10.559 --> 00:09:13.099
And we can evaluate how our prediction did.

00:09:13.099 --> 00:09:18.739
So one thing that we can do for that quick evaluation is plot the prediction versus the

00:09:18.739 --> 00:09:19.739
reality.

00:09:19.739 --> 00:09:25.299
And if our model was really good, all of our data points would fall along this y equals

00:09:25.299 --> 00:09:27.419
x line where predictions match reality.

00:09:27.419 --> 00:09:31.619
You can see we have quite a bit of variance from that line.

00:09:31.619 --> 00:09:38.780
We could look at the R-squared value of our model and see that it's not very good.

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:42.500
That's why I'm paid to give webinars and not models.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:46.140
But this hopefully gives you a sense of kind of what your workflow might start to look

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:53.179
like on R. We can even, because this is a tree-based model, look at feature importance.

00:09:53.179 --> 00:09:58.820
And so you can see that our model is emphasizing the location of our bike share station and

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:02.739
not putting as much weight on some of those factors that we created.

00:10:02.739 --> 00:10:06.900
So we have this iffy model in R. What do we want to do next?

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:10.099
Well, we could try a lot of different things to improve our model.

00:10:10.099 --> 00:10:14.739
One thing we might want to do is try something from the Python ecosystem.

00:10:14.739 --> 00:10:19.059
And so that's where kind of the heart of this webinar begins, which is how are we going

00:10:19.059 --> 00:10:23.580
to interoperate Python and R inside of this same context?

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:28.179
Well, the first thing that we'll do is create a Python code chunk.

00:10:28.179 --> 00:10:31.700
And inside of that Python code chunk, one of the things that we're going to want to

00:10:31.700 --> 00:10:35.260
do right off the bat is import some packages.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:39.859
So I'll go ahead and add the code to bring in these packages.

00:10:39.859 --> 00:10:44.179
And we can do a quick sanity check here to run the code chunk.

00:10:44.179 --> 00:10:47.619
And it appears that we have these packages loaded inside of Python.

00:10:47.619 --> 00:10:52.580
Now, I can already see in the chat that many of you are asking, how is Python managed?

00:10:52.580 --> 00:10:54.260
Where are these packages coming from?

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.099
Those are really great questions.

00:10:56.099 --> 00:11:02.460
So in the latest version of RStudio, you can use a project or global option to specify

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:07.260
what Python interpreters should be used in the context where you're mixing R and Python

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:08.260
together.

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:11.900
And so for this project, I've created a virtual environment.

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:15.900
And I've selected and told RStudio to use that virtual environment.

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:22.659
You can see that RStudio is actually aware of kind of the multitude of Python installs

00:11:22.659 --> 00:11:24.580
that are available on this server.

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:28.659
That's one of those benefits, again, of working on a server is that if Lou and I were collaborating

00:11:28.659 --> 00:11:34.580
together, we'd have this common understanding of what Python installations are available.

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:38.059
So that's where the Python engine is coming from.

00:11:38.059 --> 00:11:43.659
The Python packages themselves are coming from a tool called RStudio Package Manager.

00:11:43.659 --> 00:11:47.580
So in our case, our server is not online.

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:49.900
We have some sensitive data that lives in our environment.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:52.340
So we're not able to go reach out to the internet.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:58.539
So instead, Package Manager acts as this intermediary where we can install Python packages from

00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:03.219
a specifically governed mirror of PyPI.

00:12:03.219 --> 00:12:05.260
And so that's what you're looking at here.

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:06.900
I can search for packages.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:11.700
I can see information about those packages, how to install them, what they depend on.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:15.979
But something that's really special about this mirror is that it has a safety net that

00:12:15.979 --> 00:12:18.539
allows me to time travel as well.

00:12:18.539 --> 00:12:22.380
And so if I ever got into a situation where my Python environment wasn't working, I could

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:28.820
go backwards or forwards in time to reinstall packages from a specific point in the past.

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:31.619
So that's where these packages are coming from.

00:12:31.619 --> 00:12:34.059
Let's go ahead and start writing some code.

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:37.500
And this is where I think things get really magical.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:43.900
Because within this Python code chunk inside of my R Markdown document, I actually have

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:49.739
access to everything that I've done up until this point in R. And you can actually see

00:12:49.739 --> 00:12:55.140
the IDE here is helping me autocomplete some of the objects that are attributes of this

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:58.460
special R object that are available.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:12:59.460
And so what does that mean?

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:07.059
Well, I'm going to cheat a little bit and grab some code that I've written ahead of time.

00:13:07.059 --> 00:13:12.299
We'll just put this inside of our code chunk, and then I can walk you through it.

00:13:12.299 --> 00:13:17.700
So the first thing I'm doing, because we're going to fit this model in Python, is load

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:19.419
some training and test data.

00:13:19.419 --> 00:13:22.460
But you can see that I'm not starting from scratch.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:29.780
I'm using this magic R object to actually pull in the training and test data that I

00:13:29.780 --> 00:13:31.500
already created.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:35.460
And then I can use that as a jumping off point for fitting my model.

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:40.820
And so we're going to do a little bit of preprocessing with pandas, and then we're going to use some

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:45.659
functions from scikit-learn to fit another type of model.

00:13:45.659 --> 00:13:50.900
And one of the things that's really interesting, and why we might jump into Python here, is

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:55.380
that scikit-learn has native support for time series cross-validation.

00:13:55.380 --> 00:13:57.979
So remember I said we can't use the future to predict the past?

00:13:57.979 --> 00:14:01.979
Well, scikit-learn knows how to handle that, even in the case where you're doing a whole

00:14:01.979 --> 00:14:04.260
bunch of cross-validation fitting.

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:08.219
And so that's what we're doing here to fit an SVR model.

00:14:08.219 --> 00:14:14.059
I can go ahead and run this Python code chunk, and we can take a look at our results.

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:21.179
All right, so trainResults.mean, that's the mean of our cross-validation R-squared value.

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:24.380
And you can see, it's really bad.

00:14:24.380 --> 00:14:28.299
Okay, so I'm not a great Python model fitter.

00:14:28.299 --> 00:14:34.380
But hopefully you get the idea that we can really seamlessly reuse things back and forth.

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:38.219
And you might have noticed a couple of other things that the IDE is doing to help me with this

00:14:38.219 --> 00:14:39.659
Python development.

00:14:39.659 --> 00:14:43.059
So one of the things that I briefly mentioned is that autocomplete.

00:14:43.059 --> 00:14:48.500
And so say we wanted to use a different model from scikit-learn.

00:14:48.500 --> 00:14:52.979
You can see the IDE is providing me with all the different options that are available,

00:14:52.979 --> 00:14:55.780
all the attributes and methods of these objects.

00:14:55.780 --> 00:15:00.340
And the help for those methods, the arguments that they take, are also all going to be available

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:04.659
in the IDE with the rich autocompletion that you'd expect.

00:15:04.659 --> 00:15:09.140
The other thing that I'll point out is if we look at our environment pane, when we switch

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:14.739
to the Python context, we actually got a Python environment explorer as well.

00:15:14.739 --> 00:15:19.940
And so these objects that I'm creating inside of Python, I can actually see them and explore

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:21.700
them inside of the IDE.

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:24.739
And I could even preview them as well.

00:15:24.739 --> 00:15:29.859
So this becomes a really rich way to interactively do your work and debug problems.

00:15:29.859 --> 00:15:35.299
And you can see that even things like the filter capability inside of the IDE, as well

00:15:35.380 --> 00:15:38.979
as sort, work for these Python objects.

00:15:38.979 --> 00:15:44.020
I can also switch at any time back and forth between R and Python because the two ecosystems

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:47.780
are coexisting together inside of this notebook.

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.900
Speaking of which, there's one last trick that I want to show you.

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:56.020
So I've fit this Python model, and I have some Python predictions.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:59.780
What if I then wanted to go and do some further analysis?

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:04.500
Well, you saw how I can reuse R objects in the Python context.

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:10.260
But I can do the same thing inside of R. So inside of R, there's this magic object called

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:16.260
py that gives me access to everything that I've created so far in the Python space.

00:16:17.219 --> 00:16:23.700
And so I can go ahead and use that object to do something like this.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:30.900
If I grab some code from my cheat sheet, place it in this chunk, I'm essentially taking

00:16:32.739 --> 00:16:37.940
the Python model predictions and plotting them with ggplot2.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:41.059
And you can see a little bit here why our model fit is so bad.

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:45.539
It's because we're not capturing nearly any of the variance that is going on inside of

00:16:45.539 --> 00:16:46.020
our data.

00:16:47.140 --> 00:16:47.940
All right.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:52.580
So we've fit this model that combines R and Python together inside of a notebook.

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:54.099
What do we do now?

00:16:54.739 --> 00:17:00.179
Well, at RStudio, we're big believers that you should share your data science work early

00:17:00.179 --> 00:17:01.059
and often.

00:17:01.059 --> 00:17:06.260
This is the best way for people with domain knowledge or stakeholders to validate that

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:07.300
you're on the right path.

00:17:08.339 --> 00:17:12.979
And so one way to do that that's really powerful is through publishing.

00:17:12.979 --> 00:17:15.140
And within RStudio, we can publish.

00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:16.819
You see this blue icon here.

00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:19.380
And we can publish to a number of places.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:25.219
But within a team enterprise setting, our recommendation is to publish to RStudio Connect.

00:17:25.219 --> 00:17:27.060
And so I'll go ahead and do that.

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:30.260
You can see the ID identifies my dependencies.

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:36.180
And what happens when I click publish is that a reproducible unit is created here that contains

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:41.219
not only my code, but also things like the version of R, the version of Python, the different

00:17:41.219 --> 00:17:44.660
packages that I need to reliably reproduce this document.

00:17:45.380 --> 00:17:51.140
And so I'll go and show you the end result here on RStudio Connect, which is that same

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:52.420
rendered notebook.

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:59.380
So we have kind of all the information that I have been working up to this point, but

00:17:59.380 --> 00:18:02.739
in the context where I can easily share it with others.

00:18:02.739 --> 00:18:04.819
So I can specify who should be able to see this.

00:18:05.939 --> 00:18:12.420
And because it's that reproducible unit, at any point, I can reliably refresh this document

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:13.699
to regenerate the results.

00:18:14.339 --> 00:18:16.819
Or I could do something like set up a schedule.

00:18:16.819 --> 00:18:22.099
So my data might change over time, and I might want this notebook to re-render on a regular

00:18:22.099 --> 00:18:22.979
basis.

00:18:22.979 --> 00:18:28.579
And I can set all that up because the dependencies are intertwined in a reproducible unit with

00:18:28.579 --> 00:18:29.300
this document.

00:18:30.739 --> 00:18:35.459
Now, you might be thinking, that's great if you're a RStudio user, which probably most

00:18:35.459 --> 00:18:36.420
of you are.

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:38.420
But what about my colleagues on the Python side?

00:18:38.979 --> 00:18:43.699
Well, the same option is available for sharing your work early and often if you're coming

00:18:43.699 --> 00:18:44.900
from Python.

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:47.140
And so I want to quickly show you what that looks like.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:51.780
In the RStudio IDE, we clicked that blue Publish button.

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:56.099
And inside of Jupyter Notebooks, you can click that blue Publish button as well.

00:18:56.099 --> 00:19:00.260
But I want to show you a slightly different way that you can quickly and easily share

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:01.380
your content.

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:04.579
And that's to import content from a system like Git.

00:19:05.219 --> 00:19:08.500
So what I have here is a Git repository.

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:14.020
That Git repository contains all of the example code we've been talking about today.

00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:15.380
And it's a public repository.

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:18.020
So you can go ahead and play around with this as well if you'd like.

00:19:18.739 --> 00:19:25.060
What I'm going to do is take this Git repository and tell RStudio Connect to import that content.

00:19:25.780 --> 00:19:28.660
And so I have different branches that I can choose between.

00:19:29.619 --> 00:19:32.900
And then this repository has a number of different directories.

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:34.979
I'll go ahead and import the Jupyter Notebook.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:37.060
I'll give it a title here.

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:42.180
And what happens when we import this content is the same thing that we saw in interactive

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:43.140
publishing.

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:46.979
The environment this content depends upon is recreated.

00:19:46.979 --> 00:19:50.579
So I have a reproducible unit of work around my notebook.

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:54.900
And if I go and open up that notebook, I can see the results.

00:19:55.540 --> 00:20:01.219
So I can share this even with a non-technical user who might be intimidated by the standard

00:20:01.219 --> 00:20:02.979
Jupyter Notebook interface.

00:20:02.979 --> 00:20:06.579
Here they just have a really clean HTML document that they can read.

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:11.859
And a data scientist can specify who should be able to see this content, but also do those

00:20:11.859 --> 00:20:15.859
same things I was talking about for scheduling or re-rendering the content on demand.

00:20:17.219 --> 00:20:18.500
So we have our notebooks.

00:20:18.500 --> 00:20:20.180
We've shared them early and often.

00:20:20.180 --> 00:20:21.060
That's great.

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:23.140
We've gotten this domain feedback.

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:26.979
Maybe we iterate a couple of times and really improve that model.

00:20:27.699 --> 00:20:29.060
What do we do then?

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:33.699
How do we ensure that the model is actually being used to generate decisions?

00:20:34.579 --> 00:20:37.140
That's kind of the key task of a data science team.

00:20:37.859 --> 00:20:41.060
Well, there's two ways that we think about this at RStudio.

00:20:41.619 --> 00:20:48.660
One is to influence how decision makers are making decisions through your model.

00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:51.619
And a great way to do that is through interactive applications.

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:57.780
So many of you might be familiar with tools like Shiny, which allow you to do that in R.

00:20:58.739 --> 00:21:04.660
But we've worked hard in the last year to ensure that multilingual teams have that same capability.

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:08.099
So what you're looking at here is a Dash application,

00:21:08.099 --> 00:21:11.380
which is an interactive application written in Python.

00:21:11.939 --> 00:21:18.660
And what this application is going to allow us to do is help stakeholders understand our model.

00:21:18.660 --> 00:21:22.819
So they can come in here and click through different stations

00:21:22.819 --> 00:21:25.939
and see the forecast and the location of the station.

00:21:25.939 --> 00:21:30.420
So it's a pretty simple app, but hopefully it kind of gets your wheels turning

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:34.900
that even if you're a Python data scientist or you work with Python data scientists,

00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:39.699
they have the same ability to impact decisions by creating interactive content.

00:21:39.699 --> 00:21:43.459
And we see examples of that with Dash, with Streamlet, with Bokeh,

00:21:43.459 --> 00:21:48.900
with a wide variety of interactive Python frameworks that are supported through the RStudio stack.

00:21:50.020 --> 00:21:54.260
So that's how you might go about influencing a person with your model.

00:21:54.260 --> 00:21:58.739
But what if you need to use your model to make a whole bunch of automated decisions?

00:21:58.739 --> 00:22:02.500
Or if you need to influence not a person, but a service?

00:22:03.939 --> 00:22:08.099
One way that's common to solve that problem is by creating an API.

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:12.900
And again, there's options for doing this in R and Python.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:15.939
So on the R side, we have tools like Plumber.

00:22:15.939 --> 00:22:19.300
On the Python side, we have tools like Flask.

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:23.780
And both of these can be shared just as easily through RStudio Connect.

00:22:24.260 --> 00:22:27.619
And so I'll just quickly show you what that API might entail.

00:22:27.619 --> 00:22:30.420
Again, we have all of the same controls.

00:22:30.420 --> 00:22:34.180
And so we can look at the logs of this Plumber API.

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:35.939
We could do things like scale.

00:22:36.579 --> 00:22:40.260
If we know we're going to have thousands of requests to this API at the same time,

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:43.380
we can specify how we want the system to handle those requests.

00:22:43.939 --> 00:22:46.500
But at the end of the day, the idea is pretty simple.

00:22:46.500 --> 00:22:52.339
It's that anyone can come in and place a parameter of your model.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:56.260
In this case, we're specifying the station that we want to make a prediction for

00:22:56.819 --> 00:22:59.540
and the time horizon that we want to make a prediction for.

00:23:00.420 --> 00:23:05.619
And then those inputs are passed to our model, and the results are returned.

00:23:05.619 --> 00:23:08.500
So here we have the results of our forecast.

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:12.500
But as you can see, that passing of inputs and outputs

00:23:12.500 --> 00:23:15.060
is done in a way that machines can understand.

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:17.380
So here we have the output in JSON.

00:23:17.939 --> 00:23:20.420
And just above that, we have the request

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:25.459
that our kind of interactive exploration of this API would generate.

00:23:25.459 --> 00:23:28.579
So other systems or services or software engineers

00:23:28.579 --> 00:23:30.819
can take advantage of your model at scale.

00:23:32.339 --> 00:23:32.739
All right.

00:23:32.739 --> 00:23:34.660
So we've covered quite a bit of ground.

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:37.380
We've talked about how to make these models through notebooks.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:40.420
We've talked about the different ways that you can

00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:42.979
enhance those models and put them into production.

00:23:42.979 --> 00:23:48.020
I didn't actually show you the code for either that Dash application or this API.

00:23:48.020 --> 00:23:49.780
So that's the last thing that I wanted to do

00:23:50.339 --> 00:23:54.579
is talk a little bit about how you can get started writing this type of code.

00:23:54.579 --> 00:23:59.060
And so if I go back to the RStudio IDE, if you're an R user,

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:02.339
my recommendation is to just click New File,

00:24:02.339 --> 00:24:04.099
and you'll see a bunch of options,

00:24:04.099 --> 00:24:08.180
two of which are Shiny web applications and Plumber APIs.

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:11.939
So those are going to get you started with creating either web apps or APIs.

00:24:12.979 --> 00:24:17.300
If you're a Python user inside of the RStudio stack,

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:20.339
we looked at Jupyter notebooks.

00:24:20.339 --> 00:24:24.979
But if you want to do this type of coding for APIs or applications,

00:24:24.979 --> 00:24:27.699
you're probably going to need a little bit more robust editor.

00:24:27.699 --> 00:24:31.060
And you can use either JupyterLab or VS Code for that purpose.

00:24:31.699 --> 00:24:33.699
If I open up Visual Studio Code,

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:37.780
the kind of last thing I want to show you here

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:41.619
is just how easy that deployment of an API or an application is.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:43.699
So inside of VS Code,

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:48.339
again, I'm working off of that shared common Python environment.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:51.699
So it's easy for me to collaborate and automatically

00:24:51.699 --> 00:24:54.180
get the right Python environment as all my colleagues.

00:24:54.739 --> 00:24:57.300
I have my code here for a dash application.

00:24:58.579 --> 00:25:01.060
And then all I need to do to deploy

00:25:01.619 --> 00:25:05.219
is use a utility that we've created called rsconnect.

00:25:05.219 --> 00:25:07.939
So this is just a Python package that you can install

00:25:07.939 --> 00:25:10.739
really wherever you're writing Python code.

00:25:10.739 --> 00:25:14.339
And it has commands to help you then take that Python code

00:25:14.339 --> 00:25:17.859
and wrap it up in that reproducible context.

00:25:17.859 --> 00:25:23.140
So for example, I'll do rsconnect deploy dash to a server called dev.

00:25:23.939 --> 00:25:26.339
And it's going to run through and identify

00:25:26.339 --> 00:25:28.099
all the dependencies of this application

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:32.339
and then give me the link to the deployed app.

00:25:32.339 --> 00:25:33.859
And if we follow that link,

00:25:33.859 --> 00:25:36.579
you'll see the exact same bike share application

00:25:36.579 --> 00:25:37.540
we were looking at before.

00:25:38.020 --> 00:25:40.099
So to recap, we covered quite a bit of ground.

00:25:40.099 --> 00:25:42.180
We created that document using R and Python

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:44.339
and some really cool RStudio magic.

00:25:44.900 --> 00:25:47.380
That document was shared in a reproducible way.

00:25:47.380 --> 00:25:49.300
We talked about how Jupyter notebook users

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:52.260
can do the same type of early and often sharing.

00:25:52.260 --> 00:25:55.140
And then how we can use that model to impact decisions

00:25:55.140 --> 00:25:57.060
either through apps or APIs.

00:25:57.060 --> 00:25:59.459
And finally, how you might go about writing those things

00:25:59.459 --> 00:26:02.180
using some of the new features in the RStudio workbench.

00:26:02.180 --> 00:26:04.819
With that, I will hand things over to Lou,

00:26:05.060 --> 00:26:08.020
who's going to kind of bring us home.

