00:39:44.820 --> 00:39:45.620
Would you like to comment

00:39:45.620 --> 00:39:46.100
on that at all?

00:39:48.419 --> 00:39:49.620
Yeah, absolutely.

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:51.699
So I would tend to agree

00:39:52.419 --> 00:39:53.540
it is a bit of a mess

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:54.419
that it certainly

00:39:55.459 --> 00:39:56.739
is kind of my experience.

00:39:58.100 --> 00:39:59.939
Right now the RStudio IDE

00:40:00.820 --> 00:40:01.780
sits on top

00:40:02.419 --> 00:40:03.620
of kind of the many

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:05.060
Python management tools

00:40:05.060 --> 00:40:05.860
that are available.

00:40:06.419 --> 00:40:08.179
And so if you already have

00:40:08.179 --> 00:40:09.060
a tool of choice

00:40:09.699 --> 00:40:10.739
you saw in my demo

00:40:10.739 --> 00:40:12.820
I was using a virtual environment.

00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:15.219
If you're using something like Conda

00:40:15.219 --> 00:40:16.899
or Poetry or PyEnv

00:40:17.699 --> 00:40:18.820
the RStudio IDE

00:40:18.820 --> 00:40:20.419
will sit on top

00:40:20.419 --> 00:40:21.860
of all of those options.

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:23.620
And in fact,

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:25.219
the kind of key engine

00:40:25.219 --> 00:40:26.179
behind all of this

00:40:26.179 --> 00:40:27.540
is an open source package

00:40:27.540 --> 00:40:28.580
called Reticulate.

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:30.500
And within that package

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:32.340
you can see the different functions

00:40:32.340 --> 00:40:35.139
that help the IDE and R

00:40:35.139 --> 00:40:36.979
identify what Python environment

00:40:36.979 --> 00:40:37.479
to use.

00:40:37.879 --> 00:40:39.479
That's also something

00:40:39.479 --> 00:40:40.199
that you'll see

00:40:40.199 --> 00:40:42.040
in the options menu

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:43.080
that I mentioned

00:40:43.080 --> 00:40:44.520
where if you go inside

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:45.399
of RStudio IDE

00:40:45.399 --> 00:40:47.239
and click tools options

00:40:48.679 --> 00:40:50.040
basically any of those

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.000
Python environments

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:52.199
whether they're from Conda

00:40:52.199 --> 00:40:53.239
or Virtualenv

00:40:53.879 --> 00:40:54.919
are going to be available.

00:40:55.479 --> 00:40:56.760
Now that doesn't necessarily mean

00:40:56.760 --> 00:40:58.600
that the headaches go away.

00:40:59.239 --> 00:41:00.600
And so one of the things

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:01.479
that we're working on

00:41:01.479 --> 00:41:02.520
in the future

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:03.879
is extending the support

00:41:03.879 --> 00:41:05.239
for creating and managing

00:41:05.239 --> 00:41:06.439
those virtual environments

00:41:06.439 --> 00:41:07.959
from within the IDE as well.

00:41:08.840 --> 00:41:09.959
And so you can look out

00:41:09.959 --> 00:41:11.080
for that on the horizon.

00:41:12.199 --> 00:41:13.479
And then as Lou mentioned

00:41:13.479 --> 00:41:14.679
on the professional side

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:16.600
if you think those headaches

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:17.560
are challenging

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.239
as a single data scientist

00:41:19.239 --> 00:41:21.399
as a team of Python users

00:41:21.399 --> 00:41:23.320
that can often present

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:24.679
even more of a challenge

00:41:24.679 --> 00:41:25.719
which is one of the reasons

00:41:25.719 --> 00:41:26.679
why we're investing

00:41:26.679 --> 00:41:27.879
for those commercial teams

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:30.760
in a package management repository

00:41:30.760 --> 00:41:32.760
that supports both R and Python

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:34.760
to help make that work reproducible

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:36.760
to help IT folks say

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:38.280
what packages should be allowed

00:41:39.159 --> 00:41:40.760
as well as that kind of

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:42.520
time travel capability

00:41:42.520 --> 00:41:43.560
that I briefly showed.

00:41:44.439 --> 00:41:45.479
So that's I think

00:41:45.479 --> 00:41:47.000
a long-winded way of saying

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:48.600
well we all can commiserate

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:49.560
with the challenges

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:51.719
in Python dependency management

00:41:51.719 --> 00:41:52.600
we're going to continue

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:54.520
to invest and make it better

00:41:54.520 --> 00:41:56.600
but all of the kind of work

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:57.239
and we're standing

00:41:57.239 --> 00:41:58.840
on the shoulders of giants here

00:41:59.639 --> 00:42:00.760
is available to you

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:02.040
from within RStudio IDE.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.239
And I just wanted to add to that

00:42:05.239 --> 00:42:06.280
another plug for

00:42:07.399 --> 00:42:10.120
RStudio's own Alex Gold

00:42:10.120 --> 00:42:10.919
who's also part of

00:42:10.919 --> 00:42:12.679
the solutions engineering team

00:42:12.679 --> 00:42:14.360
is going to be doing a webinar

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:15.800
in a couple of weeks

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:17.000
on the challenges

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:17.959
of package management

00:42:17.959 --> 00:42:18.840
and how to address them.

00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:20.439
We're going to be doing

00:42:20.439 --> 00:42:21.639
a series of blog posts

00:42:21.639 --> 00:42:23.080
between now and then

00:42:23.080 --> 00:42:24.040
talking about the package

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:24.919
management problem.

00:42:25.879 --> 00:42:26.919
So I encourage

00:42:26.919 --> 00:42:28.360
anyone who's interested in that

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:29.000
to check it out.

00:42:30.679 --> 00:42:31.719
Now Sean is there any

00:42:32.280 --> 00:42:33.719
I got a favorite next question

00:42:33.719 --> 00:42:35.399
but anything that you want to

00:42:35.399 --> 00:42:36.840
jump to before I toss someone out?

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:39.560
So there was one question

00:42:39.560 --> 00:42:40.760
I really liked.

00:42:40.760 --> 00:42:42.520
It's a very RStudio question

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:43.479
which is to ask you

00:42:43.479 --> 00:42:44.760
what are the limitations?

00:42:45.800 --> 00:42:46.760
And we try to be pretty

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:47.479
up front with that.

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:50.120
So I'll just throw out there

00:42:51.159 --> 00:42:53.879
I personally use the RStudio IDE

00:42:53.879 --> 00:42:55.080
when I'm combining R

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:56.360
and Python together.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:57.560
I have friends who use

00:42:57.560 --> 00:42:59.000
the RStudio IDE

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:00.120
for all their Python work.

00:43:00.919 --> 00:43:02.120
I have other colleagues

00:43:02.120 --> 00:43:03.320
who use VS Code

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:04.280
for their Python work.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.679
So kind of our common theme

00:43:06.679 --> 00:43:07.800
is the tools should be

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:09.159
subservient to you

00:43:09.159 --> 00:43:10.280
as a data scientist

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:11.719
and not the other way around.

00:43:11.719 --> 00:43:13.320
So pick what works for you.

00:43:13.879 --> 00:43:15.560
But some of the specific limitations

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:16.679
that you might run into

00:43:16.679 --> 00:43:18.360
that we're investing to make better

00:43:18.919 --> 00:43:20.679
but you might hit today

00:43:20.679 --> 00:43:22.199
are that kind of creation

00:43:22.199 --> 00:43:23.479
of Python environments.

00:43:23.479 --> 00:43:25.080
I mentioned RStudio

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:26.280
sits on top of that

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:27.560
but it doesn't really give you

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:28.360
tools yet today

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:29.800
for creating your

00:43:29.800 --> 00:43:31.560
condor virtual environments.

00:43:31.560 --> 00:43:32.600
And then the other limitation

00:43:32.600 --> 00:43:33.479
I would call out

00:43:33.479 --> 00:43:35.239
is that the debugger

00:43:35.239 --> 00:43:36.280
inside of RStudio

00:43:36.840 --> 00:43:39.239
today is still pretty R oriented.

00:43:39.239 --> 00:43:40.919
And so if you're spending all day

00:43:40.919 --> 00:43:42.280
kind of writing a long

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:43.479
Python application

00:43:44.760 --> 00:43:46.600
and you are using a debugger

00:43:46.600 --> 00:43:48.760
as a critical element of that

00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:50.040
I would tend to recommend

00:43:50.040 --> 00:43:51.800
something like VS Code

00:43:51.800 --> 00:43:53.320
as maybe a better option.

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:56.679
So that's my favorite question

00:43:56.679 --> 00:43:57.879
talking about limitations.

00:43:58.600 --> 00:43:59.719
What was your favorite question?

00:44:00.439 --> 00:44:02.760
Mine was a closely related question

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:03.560
which was

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:05.000
I can't find it now in the list

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:05.879
but there was something

00:44:05.879 --> 00:44:06.840
to the effect of

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:08.919
can we now use Python

00:44:08.919 --> 00:44:10.199
within the IDE

00:44:10.199 --> 00:44:12.679
without a lot of shenanigans unquote.

00:44:14.679 --> 00:44:15.879
And my view on that

00:44:15.879 --> 00:44:17.719
is the most recent release

00:44:17.719 --> 00:44:19.080
RStudio 1.4

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:20.600
has lowered the bar

00:44:20.600 --> 00:44:23.639
of necessary shenanigans considerably.

00:44:23.639 --> 00:44:24.600
You want to comment on that?

00:44:26.439 --> 00:44:27.639
Yeah, I would agree.

00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:28.679
As I said

00:44:28.679 --> 00:44:29.959
I do have some colleagues

00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:33.159
especially those who know R

00:44:33.159 --> 00:44:34.280
and are learning Python

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:35.479
for the first time

00:44:35.479 --> 00:44:36.360
can be really nice

00:44:36.360 --> 00:44:37.560
to not introduce

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:38.760
yet another editor.

00:44:39.479 --> 00:44:40.280
It can be challenging

00:44:40.280 --> 00:44:41.000
when you're trying to learn

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:41.639
a new language

00:44:41.639 --> 00:44:43.479
to also be learning a new tool.

00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:45.479
And so I think

00:44:45.479 --> 00:44:46.919
if you're someone who knows R

00:44:47.639 --> 00:44:48.600
that barrier of entry

00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:49.719
is low enough now

00:44:49.719 --> 00:44:51.399
that you can get started

00:44:51.399 --> 00:44:52.439
using Python

00:44:52.439 --> 00:44:53.959
right within the RStudio IDE.

00:44:53.959 --> 00:44:55.159
And then if you want to graduate

00:44:55.159 --> 00:44:56.280
to another editor

00:44:56.280 --> 00:44:56.919
that's fine

00:44:56.919 --> 00:44:58.360
but at least you're not learning

00:44:58.360 --> 00:45:00.120
both those things at once.

00:45:00.120 --> 00:45:01.639
And I kind of echo that as well

00:45:01.639 --> 00:45:03.399
to educators that are out there.

00:45:03.399 --> 00:45:04.280
Someone asked

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:06.040
what language should I teach?

00:45:07.159 --> 00:45:08.840
Well, I think that the key

00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:10.280
is to teach

00:45:10.280 --> 00:45:11.959
what you're going to be comfortable teaching

00:45:11.959 --> 00:45:13.320
to make sure that your students

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:14.760
have a really effective

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:16.120
data science experience

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:17.159
from day one

00:45:17.159 --> 00:45:18.679
and that they're not stuck

00:45:18.679 --> 00:45:19.879
fighting their tools

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:21.320
before they're able

00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:22.600
to create their first plot

00:45:22.600 --> 00:45:24.040
whether that's a matplotlib

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:25.639
or a ggplot2.

00:45:25.639 --> 00:45:26.439
You want to give them

00:45:26.439 --> 00:45:28.120
that gratifying moment early on.

00:45:28.840 --> 00:45:29.719
And it's my belief

00:45:29.719 --> 00:45:31.399
that a lot of folks at RStudio

00:45:31.399 --> 00:45:33.159
have done a ton of awesome work

00:45:33.159 --> 00:45:35.399
to ensure that the RStudio IDE

00:45:35.399 --> 00:45:37.000
isn't going to present that hurdle

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:38.360
and isn't going to fight students.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:40.040
If you are a teacher

00:45:40.040 --> 00:45:41.560
interested in using R and Python

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:42.600
also do a quick shout out

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:44.040
to RStudio Cloud

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:45.239
which can reduce that hurdle

00:45:45.239 --> 00:45:46.360
even further

00:45:46.360 --> 00:45:47.320
by allowing folks

00:45:47.320 --> 00:45:48.600
to start writing code

00:45:48.600 --> 00:45:49.879
without installing anything

00:45:49.879 --> 00:45:50.679
on day one.

00:45:52.439 --> 00:45:54.040
And that's a good segue

00:45:54.040 --> 00:45:54.600
to a question

00:45:54.600 --> 00:45:55.719
I wanted to answer

00:45:55.719 --> 00:45:57.159
about RStudio Cloud

00:45:57.159 --> 00:45:58.199
which is we had a question

00:45:58.760 --> 00:45:59.959
on whether RStudio Server

00:45:59.959 --> 00:46:01.080
is running on-premises

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:02.360
or in the cloud or what.

00:46:03.159 --> 00:46:04.439
RStudio Server Pro

00:46:04.439 --> 00:46:07.560
typically most of our customers

00:46:07.560 --> 00:46:09.479
will install RStudio Server Pro

00:46:09.479 --> 00:46:10.040
themselves

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:11.479
but where they install it

00:46:11.479 --> 00:46:12.520
varies considerably.

00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:14.520
It could be on-prem

00:46:14.520 --> 00:46:15.239
and often is

00:46:15.239 --> 00:46:16.600
or it could be

00:46:16.600 --> 00:46:17.879
in a virtual private cloud

00:46:17.879 --> 00:46:19.479
on any of the major cloud providers.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:21.800
And so our customers do both.

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:24.439
We also have marketplace offerings

00:46:24.439 --> 00:46:25.959
for RStudio Server Pro

00:46:25.959 --> 00:46:28.199
on all three major clouds

00:46:28.199 --> 00:46:30.120
so you can search for RStudio

00:46:30.120 --> 00:46:31.560
in those cloud marketplaces

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:32.360
and that's a quick way

00:46:32.360 --> 00:46:33.080
of spinning it up.

00:46:34.040 --> 00:46:34.760
And then of course

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:35.959
rstudio.cloud

00:46:37.399 --> 00:46:38.760
as Sean just mentioned

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:40.199
is a way of getting started

00:46:40.199 --> 00:46:41.639
with similar functionality

00:46:41.639 --> 00:46:43.320
without having to install anything

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:44.679
and that's a hosted service

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:47.080
purchased on a monthly basis.

00:46:48.360 --> 00:46:50.280
There was also a question

00:46:50.280 --> 00:46:52.600
on someone asking

00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:53.320
they have a license

00:46:53.320 --> 00:46:54.760
for RStudio Server Pro

00:46:54.760 --> 00:46:55.800
is a launcher available

00:46:55.800 --> 00:46:56.600
or does that require

00:46:56.600 --> 00:46:57.639
the enterprise flavor?

00:46:58.439 --> 00:47:00.280
The launcher is actually

00:47:00.840 --> 00:47:01.399
Sean let me

00:47:02.199 --> 00:47:03.320
I thought I knew the answer to that

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:04.120
and now I caught myself.

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:04.919
Could you clarify?

00:47:05.879 --> 00:47:07.159
Yeah I would say

00:47:07.159 --> 00:47:09.320
for those kind of specific questions

00:47:09.320 --> 00:47:10.439
or if you have questions

00:47:10.439 --> 00:47:12.120
about professional products

00:47:13.159 --> 00:47:15.879
our sales team is happy to help that.

00:47:15.879 --> 00:47:18.679
That sounds like a cheesy ad

00:47:18.679 --> 00:47:20.040
but I can tell you firsthand

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:21.879
at RStudio

00:47:21.959 --> 00:47:23.560
our folks that work

00:47:23.560 --> 00:47:24.600
with our customers

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:25.800
are all in their own right

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:27.560
really talented data scientists

00:47:28.280 --> 00:47:29.239
and they'll be able to help you

00:47:29.239 --> 00:47:30.679
navigate some of these questions

00:47:31.479 --> 00:47:33.560
and we'd be the first to say

00:47:33.560 --> 00:47:34.919
you don't need a professional product

00:47:34.919 --> 00:47:36.360
